snippet.title: Kitchen Table Talk: Mother Wit, reflecting on motherhood through the lens of Black Women in America
snippet.description:
MotherWit: Black Women talking about motherhood, what it takes to be a black mom in America and how they “hold it together”.

Join us for a candid, unscripted ‘kitchen table Talk’ conversation motherhood, the raising of children, the women who came before, and the “holding the family together” through the lens of black women*

Black Women talking about motherhood, what it takes to be a black mom in America and how they “hold it together”.

Those expected to be around the Kitchen Table:
Ms. Deb Harris
Ms. Shawn Thomas
Ms. Denise Trimblesmith
Ms. Amber Jones
Dr. Tracye Moore
Rep. Dr. Gerae Peten
Dr. Treya Allen

Talk facilitated by Ms. Khara House 

*Comments made by those participating reflect their own individual viewpoint and are not those of the Murdoch Center and/or Southside Community Association.

Wit comes from a widespread root word that means "to see,know."

The Southside Community Association (the stewardship organization that is charged with oversight of the historic Murdoch Community Center) began hosting “The Lived Black Experience” (LBE) CommUnity Dialogues in June 2020 as a direct response to the BLM movement and the need to foster, grow and promote a climate of understanding, acceptance and civil dialogue around the systemic, root causes of racism, inequality and hate. The LBE presentations are lived streamed from the Murdoch Community Center’s Facebook page and include topic experts from all over the United States several times a month. After viewing this LBE please take a few minutes to complete this survey https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/BMB8RFG, in doing so you are helping us to continue to provide the community with relevant and timely programing.

If you enjoy this LBE and the other programing brought to you by the Murdoch Community Center, consider helping us continue the work with a monetary donation. You can do so by going to this link https://paypal.me/SouthsideFlagstaff. The Southside Community Association is a nonprofit, 501 C3 organization and as such donations could be tax deductible, please ask your tax professional for more information. Thank you!
